    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Experimental and Theoretical Investigations of Diffuse Reflectance Spectroscopy for Non-Invasive Tissue Characterization and Diagnosis</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Shanthi Prince</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Theoretical Investigations<br />Tissue Characterization</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Jul-2010 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0007</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">A great deal of interest is shown towards optical technologies that
have the capability of performing in situ tissue diagnosis without the need for
tissue biopsy. The ability to non-invasively detect early disease is a boon not
only to the patients but also to the medical professionals.
Diffuse reflectance spectroscopy can provide quantitative
biochemical and morphological information for tissue characterization. To
investigate this, initially skin and breast tissue are modelled as four layers.
Appropriate chromophores like, melanin, hemoglobin, lipids and fat are
modelled within each layer. Absorption coefficient is calculated based on the
concentration of each chromophores in that particular layer. Monte Carlo
simulation of light transport is studied and diffuse reflectance plot is obtained.
The simulation studies revealed that the percentage of diffuse reflectance
depends on the concentration of the chromophores present in the tissue
beneath. Thus diffuse reflectance of the tissue provides useful information to
identify the chromophores present, because different chromophores have
different spectroscopic responses to electromagnetic waves of a certain energy
band. The model can also be used to study the prognosis of disease, since
biochemical changes leads to changes in diffuse reflectance.
VB
Experimental investigations are carried out by collecting diffuse
reflectance of tissues by using an optical fiber spectrometer. This simple setup
is safe, portable and very affordable relative to other modalities. The method
involves exposure of skin surface to white light produced by an incandescent
source. The back scattered photons emerging from various layers of tissues are
detected by the spectrometer resulting in tissue surface emission profile.
Diffuse reflectance spectra are obtained from various skin conditions like
vitiligo, thrombus (due to injury), angioma, wart and mole.
To analyze the data, a spectral model (analytical model) is
developed based on the diffusion theory. The model is formulated in terms of
absorption and scattering properties of tissue. The validity and accuracy of the
model is tested using diffuse reflectance data obtained from human forearm.
The optical properties obtained are compared with the results from the
literature and found to be correlating. The values of hemoglobin concentration,
oxygen saturation, volume fraction of melanosomes, absorption and reduced
scattering coefficients obtained are different for various skin
conditions/disorders under study. These results demonstrate the diagnostic
power of diffuse reflectance.
Further, to obtain specific spectral-fingerprint, spectral analysis like
ratio analysis, difference spectra, student's t-test and principal component
analysis are performed. The results show that, there are few important spectral
regions associated with each skin condition.
Spectroscopy is useful for the measurement of time dependent
variations in the absorption and scattering of large tissue volumes. Imaging is
important when a localized heterogeneity of tissue is involved, where images
enable to differentiate it from background tissue. Discrimination between
normal-tissue and new tissue formation relies on morphological and functional
pattern recognition. The functional state of tissue can influence its optical
properties. The merging of spectroscopy and imaging enables the quantifYing
of cellular states based on a broad class of spectroscopic parameters. Hence
the fiber-based diffuse reflectance spectroscopic system is automated to
perform optical imaging.
Both direct imaging - multispectral reflectance imaging and
reconstructive imaging- functional imaging are performed. Displaying the
images at specific wavelengths enable clear visualization and discrimination
of normal and abnormal tissues. Functional optical imaging capitalizes on the
changing optical properties of tissue by using light to measure physiological
changes. Venous occlusion study reveals the functional status of the tissue.
Thus the potential of diffuse reflectance for non-invasive tissue
characterization and diagnostic capabilities are investigated.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9359">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9359</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
</table></center><br/>
